# Per Filip: "the animation in gain estimate is less choppy but sometimes
# goes faster sometimes slower" -- root-caused to CPython's GIL, not to the
# animation's own state machine. PhotonNeuronBar/DonutNeuronBar always
# compute their displayed pose from real elapsed wall-clock time
# (time.monotonic() - t0), so what's shown is always correct for *whatever*
# moment it actually gets to render -- there's no drift or accumulated
# error in the animation logic itself. The visible jitter comes from
# *when* it gets to render: the actual analysis (compute_ptc's chunked
# numpy loop, CaImAn's CNMF, NoRMCorre) runs on a background thread
# (threading.Thread in _run_gain_worker/_run_neuropil_worker), and while
# that thread is doing GIL-holding, non-vectorized Python-level work, the
# main thread's Tk event loop -- and therefore every queued
# self.after(33, self._tick) callback -- can't run at all. Once the GIL
# frees up, several skipped ticks' worth of elapsed time all land at once,
# which reads as the animation suddenly "catching up" (looking faster),
# followed by another stall (looking frozen/slower). Lowering the
# interpreter's GIL switch-interval (default 5ms) makes CPython check for
# a pending thread switch more often, shortening the longest a single
# GIL-holding stretch in the worker thread can run before yielding to the
# main thread's animation ticks -- a real, if partial, mitigation that
# doesn't touch the animation's own code (see also compute_ptc's smaller
# default chunk size below, for the same reason during the PTC step
# specifically). This can't fully eliminate the jitter -- CPython only has
# one GIL, and long single C-level calls inside CaImAn/NoRMCorre that
# don't release it internally still block regardless of switch-interval --
# but it meaningfully shortens the worst stalls without any architecture
# change (e.g. moving the analysis to a separate process, which would be
# a much bigger rewrite).
sys.setswitchinterval(0.001)

